  "text": ". The dotted lines represents basal metabolic rate (BMR). Although hypothetical, when the BMR is zero, heat loss is zero and the core or maintained temperature is equal to the ambient temperature. Thus, when the dashed black (part a), red (part b) and blue (part c) lines cross the x-axis at zero, the ambient temperature is the maintained or core temperature of the animal. example of this relationship emerged from studies on mitochondrial brown fat uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1), a protein that is required for uncoupled respiration and non-shivering thermogenesis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] 45 . The initial studies on Ucp1 -/-mice, which were carried out under conditions of thermal stress (ambient temperatures of 20-22 °C), failed to demonstrate a role for UCP1 in diet-induced thermogenesis and obesity [CITATION_3] 46 . However, when the same mice were housed at thermoneutrality, Ucp1 -/-mice exhibited increased metabolic efficiency, which resulted in increased adiposity and obesity compared with wild-type mice 47 . This switching of metabolic phenotypes between thermal stress and thermoneutral conditions is not limited to Ucp1 -/-mice. One pertinent example comes from studies on the effects of thyroid hormone on metabolism. In humans, hyperthyroidism is associated with a hypermetabolic state that is characterized by heat intolerance and fat loss, whereas hypothyroidism decreases metabolic rate to promote cold intolerance and obesity 48 . Investigators were surprised when they first examined the metabolic phenotype of mice that lacked type 2 deiodinase, an enzyme required for the conversion of prohormone thyroid hormone (T 4 ) to active thyroid hormone (T 3 ). Unlike humans with hypothyroidism, mice that lacked type 2 deiodinase did not develop metabolic dysfunction when they were housed at an ambient temperature of 22 °C. However, this discrepancy was resolved when control mice and type 2 deiodinase-knockout mice were housed at thermoneutrality (ambient temperature of 30 °C), which led to increased adiposity, hepatic steatosis and glucose intolerance in type 2 deiodinase-knockout mice 48 . The authors concluded that housing mice at an ambient temperature of 22 °C resulted in increased adrenergic activity to brown adipose tissue, which compensated for the loss of type 2 deiodinase activity and T 3 production. Together, these findings suggest that chronic housing of mice under conditions of thermal stress can mask the functions of genes that contribute to energy balance and metabolic homeostasis.",
